EDIT

Per the comments, it sounds like you're not seeing the gas usage based on the size of the array. Here's a simple way to test in Remix:

pragma solidity 0.5.2;

contract Test {
    uint256[] foo;
    uint256[] bar;

    constructor() public {
       for (uint256 i = 0; i < 5; i++) { 
           foo.push(i);
       }
       for (uint256 i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
           bar.push(i);
       }
    }

    function deleteFoo() external {
        foo.length =  0;
    }

    function deleteBar() external {
        bar.length = 0;
    }
}


In my testing, using the JavaScript VM, deleteFoo consumes 26,070 gas, and deleteBar consumes 266,267 gas.

Answer1.656:
The Hash trait Output has the AsRef and AsMut traits which allows you to interact with the hash as a byteslice ([u8]):

pub trait Hash: 'static + MaybeSerializeDebug + Clone + Eq + PartialEq {
    type Output: Member + MaybeSerializeDebug + AsRef<[u8]> + AsMut<[u8]>;

    // ... removed for brevity
}


Using the as_ref() or as_mut() on a hash will return a slice of bytes which you can use as normal:

For example:

// Iterate over a hash
let hash1 = <T as system::Trait>::Hashing::hash(1);
for hash_byte in hash1.as_ref().iter() {
    // ... do something
}


or

// Add one to the first byte of a hash
let mut hash2 = <T as system::Trait>::Hashing::hash(2);
hash2.as_mut()[0] += 1;

Answer1.657:
Arrays in Solidity are held in storage instead of memory. Pleas reference this article for a better understanding of the difference between the two. Since storage is dynamic, you cannot directly add an element to an index as that index may not exist in storage. If you wish to add an element to a dynamic storage array, you should use push() like so:

function addCandidate(string memory name) public {
    Candidate memory newCandidate = Candidate(candidateCount, name, 0);
    candidates.push(newCandidate);
}


A secondary option would be to use a mapping as mappings are more favorable than arrays within Solidity due to less complexity and cost. However, with using a mapping you may have to keep track of the length and indices separately dependent upon your specific implementation requirements.

